Hello everyone! My name is Amy. I was born and raised in south Oklahoma City. I currently live in Newcastle in McClain county. Right now, I am making phone calls for a state house campaign. I‚Äôm looking to host a voter registration drive and secure a van to drive people to the polls. 

Where is everyone from? What are some things you are doing in your communities? Is there any way we can help each other? 

I‚Äôm excited to connect with and learn from other peeps in Oklahoma!
Ways to take action with the OK Dems:  https://www.mobilize.us/okdemocrats/
Check your voter registration status: https://okvoterportal.okelections.us/
Instructions on how to register to vote: https://oklahoma.gov/elections/voter-registration/register-to-vote.html
2024 Oklahoma Elections - Voter Information Calendar: https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/elections/dates-and-deadlines/2024-voter-information-calendar.pdf
Remember to tell people to check their polling location on the voter portal. They often change from election to election. We want to make sure people are going to the right place.

Besides working on this and  down ballot campaigns in Oklahoma, we can also do things to support the Harris/Walz ticket in battleground states. I attended a zoom for Oklahoma Democrats and was introduced to a postcard campaign. I ordered quite a bit and would be happy to share. If you want to order your own use this link: https://www.turnoutpac.org/postcards/
Another resource is the "Let's Fix This" campaign on Reach. They currently have voter registration drive events in Oklahoma City.
Not trying to be a downer, but I'm not sure *anyone* works in the OK Democratic Party anymore.
I've never gotten an email response, I've DM'd people who the website says works there to no response, and the chair lives in Tulsa! The party is headquartered in OKC!

That‚Äôs fair. I haven‚Äôt really tried to interact with them much. The first thing I‚Äôve done with the party was the zoom that mentioned the postcards. I have found success with contacting local candidates directly to volunteer with them.

I saw that Washington County Democrats are supposed to meet regularly in Bartlesville (Crossing 2nd), but I haven't been. 

Y'all know anything about this?
I found my county on Facebook but haven‚Äôt been able to find Washington County for Oklahoma. The McClain County dems meet at Libby‚Äôs cafe in Goldsby the third Tuesday every month at 7 pm.
I found the Washington County Dems website that states their meeting time/place: https://www.washcodemsok.com/join-us
It looks like there is a Facebook page if you scroll down to the bottom of the website. I have found Facebook to be the best way to interact with the county groups

This is just a reminder that you can sign up to phone bank, canvass, get trainings  or take other actions at https://events.democrats.org/ in your state or in one of our battleground states (NC, PA, GA, NH, WI, PA, MI, AZ, NV). Volunteers like you make all the difference! We look forward to seeing you at an event soon.

This might be too optimistic but I believe Oklahomans have a unique opportunity to build one of the strongest Democratic coalitions in the country. Just look at what Florida did. Oklahoma is (thankfully) getting bluer and bluer every gubernatorial cycle and there‚Äôs real hope for a better future.

I think optimism is needed when building coalitions! It can be hard to be hopeful when you feel like you are a single blue dot. However, as evidenced by this server, we know we aren‚Äôt alone. I agree that we have a unique opportunity to build an even stronger Democratic base. People are already doing the work. It‚Äôs really important that we keep up this energy for all our elections and community organizing efforts!

I‚Äôve been writing postcards to swing states. It has got me thinking about how we could utilize this concept in Oklahoma as well. Voter turnout here isn‚Äôt great. Perhaps we could find a way to fund postcards to Oklahoma Dems. If anyone has any experience doing this or has any thoughts, please share! I can contact my county Dem group to see if I can do it this election cycle.
Looks like the Dems and I are on the same wavelength: https://www.mobilize.us/okdemocrats/event/656878/

Good evening! 

I‚Äôm Nat, and I‚Äôm a transplant to OK, not that you‚Äôd know it as I am ‚Äúa house divided‚Äù as I have attended both OSU and OU. I‚Äôve been trying to connect with other Dems but rural areas are overlooked. Mostly because no one runs. I can‚Äôt criticize, I‚Äôm not running (for reasons) but it is disheartening.  I know we need to fight. I know we need to recruit. But to run‚Ä¶ that‚Äôs a huge sacrifice to ask.  I will help how I can.

Our situation as a state  is genuinely unique, and it cannot be ignored.
A unique state requires a unique approach when it comes to local politics.

If you want OK to actually change, you absolutely must RESPECTFULLY, KNOWLEDGABLY and 

<<AUTHENTICALLY>>

engage with the First Nations.

Visit council-members, do homework on how tribal politics works, read histories

^^^^DO ALL OF THIS BEFORE YOU START CONTACTING AND REACHING OUT

Actually visit and engage with the urban centers of each Nation. 

Durant, OK ‚Äî for example ‚Äî for outreach within Choctaw Nation.
You absolutely can not both ignore Native America and expect to win anything of importance in Oklahoma.
Furthermore‚Äî ‚ÄúOklahoma‚Äù is a Choctaw word, meaning ‚ÄúLand of the Red People‚Äù

Clarification here‚Äî generally speaking‚Ä¶ the native voter always has their BS radar turned on
Generational experience in dealing with federals has ingrained a deep, deep, deep distrust of outsiders.

Their BS radar is a heckuva lot more sensitive than you may presume it to be.

The saying goes‚Äî ‚Äúdo not try to bulls**t an Indian‚Äù
History proves you will not succeed.

Engage in-person.

Without that bedrock, you aint goin‚Äô anywhere.
And to be entirely transparent, the complexity goes even deeper than all I have said so far‚Ä¶

I am speaking from my lived experience as a person raised in the Choctaw Nation. My subjective personal thinking, recking, rationalizing, reasonings is rooted from the Choctaw home. 

Do not take all I have said here as absolute gospel truth in regards to Native America as a whole.

The diversity between tribe to tribe cannot be underestimated .
Native America is NOT a monolith.

Retain mindfulness that no two tribes are exactly the same. 

The perspective, world view, principles, beliefs, traditions, priorities and values differ from tribe to tribe.
No one tribe can speak on behalf of another.
